<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">June 16, 2025</h2>
<a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-daily-june-16-2025/"><img class="wp-image-255609 size-thumbnail aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/AdobeStock_1215648788-scaled-e1749837186711-150x150.jpeg" alt="climate" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400"><a href="https://www.publicbooks.org/after-the-deluge-what-future-for-climate-fiction/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">Keith Woodhouse considers the future of climate fiction</span></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.newyorker.com/culture/the-weekend-essay/why-do-doctors-write" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">The long tradition of doctor-writers</span></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.thenation.com/article/society/palestinian-american-dream-sarah-aziza/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400"><a href="https://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/into-the-sun/">The apocalyptic relevance of C.F. Ramuz’s <i>Into the Sun</i></a></span></a></li>
</ul>
